    <stitle>International&#174; T 444E Diesel Engine Service, Model Year 1994 - 1998 - CRANKCASE, CRANKSHAFT, CONNECTING
        RODS AND PISTONS - Connecting Rods, Pistons and Piston Rings - Removal
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="5">
        <title>Removal</title>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>If a carbon ridge is evident at the top of the cylinder bore, it must be removed before the piston
                    and connecting rod assemblies are removed to reduce the chance of piston and ring damage during
                    removal.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a razor knife or emery board to scrape the carbon ridge from the top of the cylinder
                bore.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1200720" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figeg1/EG1381.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="472px" box="yes"/>
            <caption>Connecting Rod Locations</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting Rod Nuts (16)</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting Rod (8)</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Crankshaft</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting Rod Location Mark</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting Rod Cap (8)</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Mark each connecting rod and its respective rod cap with identification marks (cylinder
                number) before removing them from the engine. Also mark the rod caps for correct orientation to each
                rod.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Rotate the crankshaft to position the journals for removal of the connecting rod assemblies.
                Mark the connecting rod locations.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1200721" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figeg2/EG2581.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="yes"/>
            <caption>Removing the Connecting Rod Cap Mounting Nuts</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting Rod Cap</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting Rod Nut</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>The mounting nuts should turn off the connecting rod studs freely. If binding exists, check for
                    bent or damaged threads to avoid engine damage.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the two connecting rod mounting nuts. Remove the connecting rod cap.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the piston and connecting rod assemblies from the crankcase as follows:</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Rotate the engine into a vertical position (front end up).</para>
                <figure id="f1200722" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figeg1/EG1908.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="yes"/>
                    <caption>Installing the Connecting Rod Guide Protector Caps</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting Rod Nut (16)</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting Rod Cap (8)</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting Rod (8)</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting Rod Protector Caps</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Crankshaft</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Install aluminum connecting rod guide protector caps over connecting rod studs to
                    prevent damage to the crankshaft rod journals.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1200723" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figeg2/EG2582.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="472px" box="yes"/>
                    <caption>Pushing the Connecting Rod and Piston Assembly Out Of the Cylinder Bore</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Wooden Handle</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Protector Cap</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting Rod</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Crankcase</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Use a wooden or plastic handle to push the piston and rod assembly out of the cylinder
                    bore.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1200724" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figeg2/EG2583.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="472px" box="yes"/>
                    <caption>Removing the Connecting Rod and Piston Assembly from the Crankcase</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Crankcase</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Protector Cap</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting Rod</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Once the piston rings are free of the cylinder bore, remove the assembly from the top of
                    the crankcase.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Mark each connecting rod and its respective bearing cap with the cylinder number from which
                they were removed.
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
